<TITLE> 'Women mustn't be lawyers' </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 5 (bdnews24.com)Women lawyers have been threatened through a letter, purported to be job of a militant group, not to work and follow Western lifestyle, a leader of the bar said Tuesday. Dhaka Lawyers' Association president Mokhlesur Rahman said the letter he received on Sunday gave a deadline June 1for the women lawyers to respond. "The letter was computer composed and was sent from Sadarghat post office," he said. Mokhlesur said he believed the letter was from "some Islamic fundamentalist militant group". A leading woman practitioner said she would not be deterred by such threats. The nine-sentence letter said Bangladeshi women should not take up the legal profession, be out and about like their Western counterparts, and pursue a career. "If anyone does otherwise, we will take serious steps," the letter said. "They cannot browbeat us into submission. We are going to continue to work as usual," Shamima Akhtar Shammi, a former general secretary of Dhaka Lawyers Association told bdnews24.com. bd
